Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 72nd Weekly Dose of Optimism. We=E2=80=
=99re feeling optimistic over here at Not Boring HQ =E2=80=94 maybe it=E2=
=80=99s the holiday spirit or maybe it=E2=80=99s the constant drip of world=
-changing, positive news we keep on getting to share with you each week. Ei=
ther way, we=E2=80=99ll take it.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Alto [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/8c54707d-fae5-4891-a274-f4e633410cac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Alto [ https://substack.com/redirect/6006c820-934e-4e31-af0b-6b6914d50650?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] allows =
individuals to invest in alternative assets with their retirement funds thr=
ough a self-directed IRA. It=E2=80=99s perfect for long-term investors in c=
rypto, fine art, real estate, private credit that want to significantly red=
uce their tax burden in the future.=C2=A0Here=E2=80=99s an example of how i=
nvesting with a Roth IRA can reduce your future tax burden:
Let's say you make a $10,000 investment in an asset with a Roth IRA. By the=
 time you're 59 and a half, that investment has increased in value to $100,=
000.=C2=A0
If you invested with non-qualified cash, you could pay up to 20% in capital=
 gains taxes over the lifetime of this investment, meaning up to $18,000 of=
 potential gains is lost to taxes. The Roth IRA allows you to potentially a=
void the entire tax liability, meaning $0 on the gains is lost to taxes. Of=
 course, IRA rules and regulations apply, and you should seek advice from a=
 tax professional when making investments.
Alto [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c54707d-fae5-4891-a274-f4e633410cac?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] makes i=
nvesting in alts with a Roth IRA easy. Even better, Alto just launched Alto=
 Marketplace [ https://substack.com/redirect/6006c820-934e-4e31-af0b-6b6914=
d50650?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
, a capital raise platform that connects individual accredited investors to=
 leading funds and exclusive opportunities.
=20
(1) Introducing Gemini: our largest and most capable AI model [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/48f59d7e-9ee4-4fec-862b-5c980a082c6a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Google
Gemini is the result of large-scale collaborative efforts by teams across G=
oogle, including our colleagues at Google Research. It was built from the g=
round up to be multimodal, which means it can generalize and seamlessly und=
erstand, operate across and combine different types of information includin=
g text, code, audio, image and video.
Google launched Gemini, its newest and most advanced AI model yet. The mode=
l is natively multimodal, meaning it can pretty seamlessly operate against =
text, code, audio, image and video and it=E2=80=99s highly performant, beat=
ing GPT4 on both text and multimodal performance benchmarks.=20
(To be fair, as others have noted, it uses a different method than GPT-4 in=
 the benchmark (CoT32 vs. 5-shot, respectively, and the video is not as one=
-shot as it seems [ https://substack.com/redirect/80fd100b-46cf-42c7-a519-8=
69a3208285a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] and relied on more sophisticated prompts than the ones shown in the v=
ideo.)
But still! In Gemini, we have the (pretty advanced!) beginnings of an AI mo=
del that you could imagine weaving its way into how we go about daily life.=
 It=E2=80=99s not just a text summarizer or image identifier (although it d=
oes those things better than any model in the world.) It=E2=80=99s a cohesi=
ve model that you could easily imagine enhancing all of Google=E2=80=99s ex=
isting core products, but, perhaps more importantly, powering a whole new s=
uite of more immersive future products. Perhaps all Google Glass needed was=
 Gemini.
From an industry perspective, this was a pretty strong move from Google. It=
 wasn=E2=80=99t around some planned Demo Day, nor was it an overly reactive=
 response to an OpenAI breakthrough. In my opinion, Google frankly didn=E2=
=80=99t need to launch Gemini yet. But it did =E2=80=94 reminding all of it=
s competitors that they=E2=80=99re still Google and, likely, the leader in =
AI. This will, of course, prompt some kind of response from OpenAI or Meta =
or Anthropic over the next couple of weeks, which will in turn pull up some=
 previously scheduled advancement from Google. This is acceleration.
One fun fact about Gemini: Google co-founder Sergei Brin was a core contrib=
utor on the technical paper behind Gemini. My man is worth over $100B and s=
till cooking in the lab! (h/t @linasbeliunas [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/1ae38cd7-27ce-4d71-8b43-f0162918d7c1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] for the find)
(2) DARPA-Funded Research Leads to Quantum Computing Breakthrough [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/c4746c30-bbc0-480f-aaaf-0bf12152e5b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From DARPA
A team of researchers working on DARPA=E2=80=99s Optimization with Noisy In=
termediate-Scale Quantum devices (ONISQ) program has created the first-ever=
 quantum circuit with logical quantum bits (qubits), a key discovery that c=
ould accelerate fault-tolerant quantum computing and revolutionize concepts=
 for designing quantum computer processors.
DARPA researchers have developed quantum circuits that utilize logical quan=
tum bits (qubits), which are essential for fault-tolerant quantum computing=
=2E Logical qubits differ from physical=
 qubits in that they are error-correct=
ed and can maintain their quantum state more reliably.=20
Quantum computing is generally error-prone due to the delicate nature of qu=
bits. Unlike the classical bits we use in regular computers, which are eith=
er 0 or 1, qubits can exist in multiple states at once. This makes them bot=
h incredibly powerful for certain computations and very sensitive to their =
environment. On Moment of Zen [ https://substack.com/redirect/8f7c3190-3c2a=
-43d3-ac70-59dbe4cb7276?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Guillaume Verdon/BasedBeffJezos said that error correcti=
on uses up ~99.9999% of the computing resources in a quantum computer. =20
Logical qubits help solve this error issue by grouping together multiple ph=
ysical qubits to create a more stable and error-resistant unit, allowing fo=
r corrections of errors that occur in individual qubits.=20
Creating logical qubits is a big step in quantum computing because it not o=
nly addresses that fundamental challenge of error correction but also paves=
 the way for more efficient and scalable quantum computing architectures =
=E2=80=94 so we can tackle the really big problems!
(3) Thalamic deep brain stimulation in traumatic brain injury: a phase 1, r=
andomized feasibility study [ https://substack.com/redirect/12b80880-fb30-4=
364-839c-21bd182e979c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Nature
Six participants with msTBI, who were between 3 and 18 years post-injury, u=
nderwent surgery with electrode placement guided by imaging and subject-spe=
cific biophysical modeling to predict activation of the CL/DTTm tract. The =
primary efficacy measure was improvement in executive control indexed by pr=
ocessing speed on part B of the trail-making test=E2=80=A6Processing speed =
on part B of the trail-making test improved 15% to 52% from baseline, excee=
ding the 10% benchmark for improvement in all five cases.
A promising study showed that electrode brain implants improved cognitive f=
unction on a group of five people that suffered from traumatic brain injury=
=2E Over 5 million people in the US alo=
ne are permanently disabled from a tra=
umatic brain injury and there hasn=E2=80=99t been much in the way of promis=
ing therapies.
Dr. Schiff and his team identified the central lateral nucleus as a key hub=
 for attention and cognitive functions and hypothesized that stimulating th=
is area with electronodes could help improve cognitive function. The sample=
 size (only 6 participants) was small, but it appears Dr. Schiff=E2=80=99s =
hypothesis is correct. It=E2=80=99ll be exciting to watch companies like Ne=
uralink (and its competitors) race to commercialize the research behind the=
se types of studies over the coming years, to bring a bit of relief to folk=
s suffering from brain damage.=20
(4) Self-copying RNA vaccine wins first full approval: what=E2=80=99s next?=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/d6ceb70e-db9b-4bcc-9e42-b923ef252428?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Elie Dolgin for Nature
The approval of yet another RNA-based vaccine for COVID-19 might not seem m=
omentous. But the endorsement last week [ https://substack.com/redirect/257=
37ec7-c931-4e02-ab17-143663c8964f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] by Japanese authorities of a jab against SARS-C=
oV-2 constructed using a form of RNA that can make copies of itself inside =
cells =E2=80=94 the first =E2=80=98self-amplifying=E2=80=99 RNA (saRNA) gra=
nted full regulatory approval anywhere in the world =E2=80=94 marks a pivot=
al advance.
Much has been written about mRNA=E2=80=99s 20 year path to real-world appli=
cability during the Covid pandemic. But that=E2=80=99s likely just the begi=
nning of RNA=E2=80=99s story when it comes to how to develop medicines and =
treat diseases. ARCT-154, a covid vaccine recently approved in Japan, becam=
e the first 'self-amplifying' RNA (saRNA) drug ever approved. saRNA technol=
ogy represents a significant advancement over conventional mRNA vaccines, o=
ffering potentially stronger and longer-lasting immune responses with lower=
 doses. For example, ARCT-154 requires one-tenth to one-sixth as much vacci=
ne per person as other RNA-based COVID-19 booster jabs =E2=80=94 leading to=
 lower production costs and less side effects.=20
Yes, the first vaccine is a Covid vaccine, but the technology opens the doo=
r to more versatile and efficient treatments for everything from the common=
 flu to cancer.=20
(5) Colonizing Mars isn't a rocket problem [ https://substack.com/redirect/=
8c9c9b4e-5749-4f2d-bd58-03e1b590687c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNu=
aMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Elliot Hershberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/65b8f94b-a134-4b52-bb3f-49=
8fe95d62d4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for Century of Bio
As rockets get cheaper and bigger, the bottleneck for space colonization wi=
ll be our ability to support biological life outside of Earth=E2=80=99s atm=
osphere.
Our friend and Not Boring Biotech Partner Elliot Hershberg [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/65b8f94b-a134-4b52-bb3f-498fe95d62d4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] explores the landscape of bi=
otech-enabled sustainable space exploration.  He breaks down ideas like:
Microbial Solutions for Space Habitats
Biotech-based Food Production
Medicine Manufacturing in Space
Materials and Construction
and provided a techno-economic analysis for space biomanufacturing. In Elli=
ot=E2=80=99s view, colonizing Mars and deep space exploration is as much as=
 biotech problem as it is a rocket problem. Seems like the rocket problem i=
s well on its way to being covered =E2=80=94 thanks Elon =E2=80=94 but we=
=E2=80=99ll need a whole new class of optimistic biotechnologists to make s=
ure we know how to biologically survive and thrive once we get to Mars and =
beyond.
BONUS: Age of Miracles, Episode 8: The Fusion Marathon
Packy here. There=E2=80=99s a joke that fusion is always 30 years away. Tha=
t joke is no longer true. It=E2=80=99s going to be here within a decade. Wh=
ile we still don=E2=80=99t have commercial fusion after 80 years of researc=
h and development, the main metric in fusion - the triple-product - has act=
ually been improving faster than Moore=E2=80=99s Law since the 1970s. It=E2=
=80=99s grown by five orders of magnitude!=20
In this episode, we get you ready for the coming fusion boom by explaining =
how fusion works, exploring the different approaches physicists have pursue=
d since the 1950s, and cover the history of the multi-decade international =
race to create energy the same way stars do.=20
You can listen on Spotify [ https://substack.com/redirect/0122ccc4-f2f5-4c9=
b-9505-25c920a60304?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ], Apple [ https://substack.com/redirect/ce0af98c-05c0-4473-a28=
8-40e5286c2d30?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU ], YouTube [ https://substack.com/redirect/7d21bf58-a2c4-4700-b9c7-f=
09524f8ffa6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ], or wherever you listen to podcasts. Enjoy!
P.S. A couple of weeks ago, we highlighted Bloomberg=E2=80=99s reporting th=
at the US was leading a group of nations in a commitment to triple nuclear =
capacity by 2050 at the COP28 Climate Summit. It happened [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/08fae4b0-7dde-4d61-a0a5-bc5364f4e484?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]! More than 20 countries launc=
hed the Declaration to Triple Nuclear Energy.=20
The Declaration covers a bunch of the things we=E2=80=99ve discussed on Age=
 of Miracles:=20
Mobilize investment in nuclear through innovative financing options.=20
Invite World Bank, international financial institutions, and regional banks=
 to include nuclear in their lending policies.
Commit to small modular reactors and advanced reactors for power generation=
 and wider industrial applications for decarbonization.
Support the development of nuclear for hydrogen or synthetic fuels producti=
on.
Promote resilient supply chains, including for fuel.
Big win for nuclear, and if they follow through, for the world.=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. If you have some time this weekend, check=
 out Alto. [ https://substack.com/redirect/8c54707d-fae5-4891-a274-f4e63341=
0cac?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Tuesday.
