 0 20px 0;">DARPA researchers have developed quantum circuits that utilize =
logical quantum bits (qubits), which are essential for fault-tolerant quant=
um computing. Logical qubits differ from physical qubits in that they are e=
rror-corrected and can maintain their quantum state more reliably. </p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Quantum computing is generally error-prone due to the d=
elicate nature of qubits. Unlike the classical bits we use in regular compu=
ters, which are either 0 or 1, qubits can exist in multiple states at once.=
 This makes them both incredibly powerful for certain computations and very=
 sensitive to their environment. On </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/=
redirect/8f7c3190-3c2a-43d3-ac70-59dbe4cb7276?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64);=
 text-decoration: underline;">Moment of Zen</a><span>, Guillaume Verdon/Bas=
edBeffJezos said that error correction uses up ~99.9999% of the computing r=
esources in a quantum computer.  </span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, =
64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Logical qubit=
s help solve this error issue by grouping together multiple physical qubits=
 to create a more stable and error-resistant unit, allowing for corrections=
 of errors that occur in individual qubits. </p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, =
64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Creating =
logical qubits is a big step in quantum computing because it not only addre=
sses that fundamental challenge of error correction but also paves the way =
for more efficient and scalable quantum computing architectures &#8212; so =
we can tackle the really big problems!</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>(3) </spa=
n><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/12b80880-fb30-4364-839c-=
